HELM FOR KUBERNETES: 
========================================

1. WHAT IS HELM?
----------------
Helm is the package manager for Kubernetes.
It helps you package, share, and deploy complex applications easily.

Think of it like:
- apt or yum for Kubernetes.
- Instead of applying many YAML files manually, you use one simple command.

Example:
helm install myapp ./mychart

This command deploys your entire application (Deployments, Services, Configs, etc.) in one go.


2. WHY USE HELM?
----------------
Without Helm:
- You manage multiple YAML files manually.
- Upgrades and rollbacks are manual and error-prone.
- Hard to reuse the same setup for multiple environments.

With Helm:
- Combines all YAMLs into one “Chart”.
- Configuration is handled via “values.yaml”.
- Rollbacks and upgrades are easy.
- Enforces standard folder structure and reusability.


3. KEY HELM CONCEPTS
--------------------
Chart          → A package of Kubernetes YAML files.
Release        → A deployed instance of a Chart.
Repository     → A collection of Charts (like DockerHub for Helm).
values.yaml    → Configuration file that defines variables and parameters.
templates/     → Folder containing Kubernetes YAML templates.
Chart.yaml     → Metadata about the Chart (name, version, description).


4. INSTALLING HELM
------------------
Linux/macOS:
  curl https://raw.githubusercontent.com/helm/helm/main/scripts/get-helm-3 | bash

Windows (using Chocolatey):
  choco install kubernetes-helm

Verify installation:
  helm version


5. STRUCTURE: 
-------------------------------
Command:
  helm create myapp

This creates a directory:
  myapp/
  ├── Chart.yaml
  ├── values.yaml
  ├── charts/
  └── templates/


6. UNDERSTANDING STRUCTURE
--------------------------
Chart.yaml        - Metadata about the chart.
values.yaml       - Central configuration file.
templates/        - Kubernetes resource templates (Deployment, Service, etc.).
_helpers.tpl      - Template helpers for naming and labels.



charts.yaml
https://helm.sh/docs/topics/charts



7. DEFAULT DEPLOYMENT TEMPLATE (EXAMPLE)
----------------------------------------
apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: {{ include "myapp.fullname" . }}
spec:
  replicas: {{ .Values.replicaCount }}
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app.kubernetes.io/name: {{ include "myapp.name" . }}
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app.kubernetes.io/name: {{ include "myapp.name" . }}
    spec:
      containers:
        - name: {{ .Chart.Name }}
          image: "{{ .Values.image.repository }}:{{ .Values.image.tag }}"
          ports:
            - containerPort: {{ .Values.service.port }}

The double curly braces {{ }} are template variables replaced with actual values from values.yaml.


8. CUSTOMIZE YOUR APP
---------------------
Edit values.yaml as follows:

replicaCount: 2

image:
  repository: nginx
  tag: "1.25"

service:
  type: ClusterIP
  port: 80

This will deploy an Nginx app with 2 replicas running on port 80.


9. INSTALL YOUR CHART
---------------------
Run:
  helm install mynginx .

Check deployed resources:
  kubectl get all


10. PREVIEW (Render YAMLs before applying)
------------------------------------------
  helm template .

This displays the YAML files that Helm will generate and apply.


11. UPGRADE AND ROLLBACK
------------------------
If you change something in values.yaml (for example, image tag), upgrade with:
  helm upgrade mynginx ./myapp

If something goes wrong, rollback easily:
  helm rollback mynginx 1


12. UNINSTALL
-------------
To remove the release:
  helm uninstall mynginx


13. USING PUBLIC HELM CHARTS
----------------------------
Example: Install the NGINX Ingress Controller

  helm repo add ingress-nginx https://kubernetes.github.io/ingress-nginx
  helm repo update
  helm install my-ingress ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx

This deploys a fully functional ingress controller in one command.


14. HELM CHART LIFECYCLE COMMANDS
---------------------------------
helm create      - Create a new chart.
helm lint        - Validate chart syntax.
helm template    - Render templates locally.
helm install     - Deploy chart to the cluster.
helm list        - List installed releases.
helm upgrade     - Upgrade a release to a new version.
helm rollback    - Rollback to a previous version.
helm uninstall   - Delete a release from the cluster.


15. REAL-WORLD USE CASES
------------------------
Bitnami/nginx                 - Deploys an Nginx web server.
Bitnami/mysql or postgresql   - Deploys databases.
prometheus-community/kube-prometheus-stack - Deploys monitoring setup.
fluent/fluent-bit             - Deploys log collection agents.
ingress-nginx/ingress-nginx   - Deploys an ingress controller.


16. QUICK MENTAL MODEL
----------------------
Use kubectl apply -f when:
  Deploying simple YAML files manually.

